Many schools have clubs or esports teams dedicated to playing video games. But did you know that theres a club at UCSC that actually makes them?

The Game Design and Art Collaboration (GDA) is a student-run club at UCSC. According to their [website](https://gdacollab.com/), they run a yearly program called Mock Studio in which students work together to develop a video game. They also host workshops and game jams to teach students about game development.

The GDA recently released their newest game, Well Witches, in June of this year. Its [page](https://game-design-art-collab.itch.io/well-witches) describes it as a co-op bullet hell roguelite, specifically requiring two players. It can be played in a browser, or downloaded for Windows, Linux, or Mac. The story centers on two witches named Aloe and Vervain, who are attempting to find ingredients to help their sick cat, Hex.

Every academic year, the GDA makes one game in their Mock Studio. Ideas for the game are pitched in the fall quarter, and development begins in winter. The whole process takes around 6 months. Other games made by GDA in the past include Malisense, TacoCat, and Asterion. They have also held a number of game jams, in which a bunch of developers each work on small, individual projects. In total, the [itch.io page](https://game-design-art-collab.itch.io/) for the GDA lists 19 different projects.

The GDAs ability to consistently release original, made-from-scratch games shows that you dont need a large studio with lots of resources to make games. Obviously, GDAs games are not as high quality as those made by professionals, but it is still impressive that they are able to make them in only a few months. 

In recent years, the impact that games made by small developers can have has become more and more apparent. While the popularity of big AAA games begins to decline, indie games have become increasingly popular. The success of these games shows that creativity and passion matters more than having a huge budget. While games in the past have solely been a form of entertainment, video games can also be a form of art. Video games incorporate a number of other art forms, such as music, visuals, and storytelling, and their interactive nature allows them to use these in ways that other mediums, such as movies, cannot. For example, they can allow the audience to fully immerse themselves in the visual environment, or tell a story that responds to the players actions. Ultimately, the passion and creativity behind  a work of art matters more than how technically impressive it is, which is why people dont like AI art. If we view games as a form of art and not simply a product, then it makes sense that a small, passionate developer could create a more engaging experience than a massive corporation.

The GDA serves as a way for students to express their creativity while learning practical game design skills  and creating a real, functional product. Its members may someday take these skills and become professional game designers, artists, writers, or coders. This clubs unique approach allows it to build community and useful skills in a way that a typical class might not be able to. It serves as both an asset for our school, and a reminder of the power of creativity and collaboration.
